WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.520
So, thank you, everyone, for joining us

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:05.760
to this session, Teaching Data Science.

00:00:06.480 --> 00:00:09.180
And please welcome James Wade.

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:17.200
Well, good afternoon, everybody.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:19.400
I'm really excited to be here today

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:22.959
to talk about generative AI and Posit Academy,

00:00:22.959 --> 00:00:25.160
and potentially the impacts of generative AI

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:27.200
on coding education overall.

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:30.639
An alternative title I could have given this talk

00:00:30.639 --> 00:00:34.160
is How I Learned I Was Wrong About Generative AI.

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:37.680
To say what I mean by that, I first want to tell you

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:41.599
about my experience with Academy at Dow, where I work.

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:45.599
We've had around 200 researchers that have taken,

00:00:45.599 --> 00:00:47.520
have participated in the program.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:50.720
And to give you an idea of who these people are,

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:53.680
they're typically chemists, chemical engineers,

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:54.799
maybe a physicist,

00:00:54.799 --> 00:00:57.599
somebody with a strong technical background

00:00:57.599 --> 00:01:00.080
who often has a PhD in this technical subject.

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:02.959
The learners themselves are more or less

00:01:02.959 --> 00:01:06.160
evenly split between R and Python.

00:01:07.199 --> 00:01:11.919
What's more, they don't really identify as a data scientist.

00:01:11.919 --> 00:01:14.559
They are part of a growing community

00:01:14.559 --> 00:01:16.959
we have internally of citizen data scientists,

00:01:16.959 --> 00:01:19.360
which you might have your own definition in your head,

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:21.919
but for us, what it means is somebody who's interested

00:01:21.919 --> 00:01:24.480
in applying concepts of data science to their work,

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:26.720
but doesn't identify as a data scientist

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:28.559
as the core function of their role.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:34.959
Now, when I started playing with large language models

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:37.360
and generative AI capabilities,

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:39.440
I got really excited about them.

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:42.080
I have a number of examples of some capabilities

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:44.400
that I imagine you might be familiar with

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:46.639
that can really turbocharge your own experience

00:01:46.639 --> 00:01:47.919
for how you can write code.

00:01:48.639 --> 00:01:51.120
And I thought that the same was going to apply

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:53.279
to the Academy participants.

00:01:53.279 --> 00:01:54.400
We'd train them up.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:57.040
They would go off and create amazing things.

00:01:58.480 --> 00:02:01.519
But when I asked them, they told me

00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:03.839
they didn't really like these coding assistants.

00:02:04.639 --> 00:02:06.720
Out of five stars, they gave them,

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:09.919
over half of the learners gave them two out of five.

00:02:09.919 --> 00:02:10.960
Now, I don't know about you,

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:13.440
but if you're looking on Yelp or Google Maps

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:16.559
for restaurants around here to go to for dinner tonight,

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:19.199
you're probably not going to go to the two-star ones.

00:02:19.199 --> 00:02:19.839
Neither will I.

00:02:20.639 --> 00:02:23.279
So what gives?

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:26.320
Why aren't these learners finding

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:28.960
the AI coding assistants to be helpful?

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:31.679
To answer that question,

00:02:31.679 --> 00:02:33.600
I want to ask another question.

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:35.440
And I'll also introduce you

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:37.679
to somebody named Andy Matuszak.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:40.639
He's an independent researcher

00:02:40.639 --> 00:02:42.800
who explores tools for thought

00:02:43.759 --> 00:02:46.240
and is a skeptic but extremely interested

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:49.119
in how AI can augment education.

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:51.759
He has a fantastic lecture

00:02:51.759 --> 00:02:53.520
that I encourage you all to go watch

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:54.639
called How Might We Learn,

00:02:55.679 --> 00:02:59.839
where he asks a very important question for learning.

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:03.039
What were the most rewarding,

00:03:03.759 --> 00:03:05.600
high-growth periods of your life?

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:08.320
I'd like for all of you to take a second

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:11.520
and think about what might this be for each of you.

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:14.240
When he asked people this question,

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:15.440
two themes emerged.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:18.639
Number one, learning wasn't the point.

00:03:19.839 --> 00:03:21.759
Rather, there was some other objective

00:03:21.759 --> 00:03:24.240
that they had to go learn something to go do.

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:28.720
Secondly, learning, it really worked.

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:33.039
How many of you have seen a new package come out

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:34.800
or a new capability you want to go learn?

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:37.360
You started to dive in and you hit a wall.

00:03:39.039 --> 00:03:41.600
Of course, these high-growth, rewarding experiences

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:43.279
should have the opposite impact of that.

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:48.080
So let's go back to these coding assistants.

00:03:48.800 --> 00:03:49.520
What's missing?

00:03:50.479 --> 00:03:52.880
Why aren't they providing this rewarding,

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:54.160
high-growth experience?

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:58.320
The answer for me is threshold concepts.

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:02.320
Now, if you're like me, maybe six months ago,

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:04.320
you have no idea what threshold concepts are.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:05.919
So let's define them.

00:04:07.279 --> 00:04:10.240
There's a number of characteristics,

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:11.919
and I'm certainly no expert in this,

00:04:11.919 --> 00:04:14.399
but some of the key points are, number one,

00:04:15.119 --> 00:04:17.040
these are ideas that once you understand them,

00:04:17.839 --> 00:04:20.880
they transform your perception and approach

00:04:20.880 --> 00:04:22.720
to a discipline or a topic.

00:04:24.399 --> 00:04:29.200
Number two, these threshold concepts must be encountered.

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:30.799
You can't be told them.

00:04:33.679 --> 00:04:35.519
When you think about these threshold concepts,

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:39.679
think about struggle and embracing the struggle.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:42.959
They have some other important characteristics

00:04:42.959 --> 00:04:44.799
that can guide us and maybe give us a hint

00:04:45.279 --> 00:04:49.679
at why coding assistants don't allow us to master them.

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:52.239
Number one, they're troublesome.

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:54.559
They might be conceptually difficult,

00:04:54.559 --> 00:04:57.519
and they might challenge our existing ways

00:04:57.519 --> 00:04:59.040
of thinking about a subject.

00:04:59.839 --> 00:05:01.519
Number two, they're liminal.

00:05:02.559 --> 00:05:04.640
We might not learn in a linear fashion.

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:06.959
We have to take some steps back

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:09.279
as we're trying to take some of these steps forward.

00:05:09.279 --> 00:05:11.119
We get confused along the way.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:13.200
They're transformatives,

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:15.519
where we're able to recognize new patterns,

00:05:15.519 --> 00:05:18.160
have new revelations, really have new understanding.

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:20.880
And lastly, they're irreversible.

00:05:21.839 --> 00:05:25.279
Once you learn these concepts, you can't unlearn them.

00:05:26.399 --> 00:05:28.480
Now, I want to take you back

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:31.760
to my own rewarding high-growth period in my life.

00:05:32.559 --> 00:05:36.160
Also, the reason why I wasn't at PositConf last year.

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:38.239
It's these two.

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:39.200
It's these two.

00:05:41.119 --> 00:05:42.959
On the left is the troublemaker, Henry,

00:05:42.959 --> 00:05:46.000
and on the right is the sweet child, Penelope.

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:48.239
They taught me a lot.

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:51.440
Number one, they taught me

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:53.839
that asking for help means that you care,

00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:58.320
that self-care is not selfish,

00:05:59.679 --> 00:06:02.720
and that incomplete to-do lists are okay.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:05.359
Now, a couple of years ago,

00:06:05.359 --> 00:06:07.040
if I were sitting in this audience and I heard these,

00:06:07.040 --> 00:06:09.679
I'd be like, okay, these are trite cliches, whatever.

00:06:11.359 --> 00:06:12.959
But to some extent, that's the point.

00:06:12.959 --> 00:06:14.799
I didn't experience this.

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:16.160
I didn't go through the struggle,

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:19.359
and so these concepts wouldn't have meant much to me

00:06:19.359 --> 00:06:21.200
until I experienced them.

00:06:22.799 --> 00:06:25.519
So let's bring this back to data science and to Academy.

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:30.079
Part of Academy is to impart you with the skills

00:06:30.079 --> 00:06:32.480
to use all of the packages of the hex stickers

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:34.079
I'm sure you recognize on the right here.

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:37.040
We can learn these threshold concepts

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:40.320
like tidy data enables efficient analysis

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:44.880
or modular code enhances reusability and clarity,

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:47.839
or maybe visualization is a tool

00:06:47.839 --> 00:06:49.920
for exploration and communication.

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:53.600
Now, if you've been coding in R for a while,

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:56.320
you probably can resonate with these,

00:06:56.320 --> 00:06:59.440
but it might be hard for you to explain to a beginner

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:04.640
to a beginner why these concepts are so transformational.

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:09.839
Beyond threshold concepts, chat GBT

00:07:09.839 --> 00:07:12.320
or maybe pick your favorite AI coding assistant,

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:14.480
there's a couple of things it won't give you,

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:18.480
and it's beyond these threshold concepts.

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:20.000
It's these learning dispositions.

00:07:22.239 --> 00:07:26.000
One of these is a sense of the possible or agency,

00:07:26.880 --> 00:07:28.640
and this really comes through the mentorship

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:30.079
that's part of Academy.

00:07:31.119 --> 00:07:35.359
You leave this understanding that you can tackle a problem.

00:07:35.359 --> 00:07:37.279
You have new capabilities and a persistence

00:07:37.279 --> 00:07:38.480
that you didn't have before.

00:07:40.079 --> 00:07:42.320
Another learning disposition is flexibility.

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:46.559
You can expand the palette of possibilities

00:07:46.559 --> 00:07:50.160
of the types of problems you're willing to encounter

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:51.440
or willing to take on.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.519
You're not so constrained as you might not have been before.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:57.839
Okay, so let's zoom out a bit.

00:07:58.799 --> 00:08:00.160
You've heard me talk about all these things

00:08:00.160 --> 00:08:03.200
that these AI coding assistants won't do for you.

00:08:03.839 --> 00:08:05.519
They don't give you these threshold concepts.

00:08:05.519 --> 00:08:07.279
They don't give you these learning dispositions.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:08.799
Should we throw them away?

00:08:10.640 --> 00:08:12.000
I would certainly answer no,

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:15.119
but it's important to think of how we're going to use these.

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:18.399
Let's go through some analogies.

00:08:19.359 --> 00:08:22.079
Many of you may have heard a phrase popularized

00:08:22.079 --> 00:08:23.600
by Steve Jobs in the 19,

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:26.239
I think it was in 1990,

00:08:26.239 --> 00:08:28.880
of computers as the bicycle for the mind.

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:34.000
The analogy here is that we're walking along

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.080
and computers allow us to move much faster,

00:08:37.119 --> 00:08:38.960
but there's an important implication here.

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:43.599
It's that, yes, with these bicycles, we can go faster,

00:08:43.599 --> 00:08:45.200
but we still have to steer.

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:48.400
What's more, we have to know where we're going

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:51.280
and we might have to fall a few times.

00:08:52.239 --> 00:08:55.840
Maybe we need to continue maybe butchering the analogy here.

00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:57.119
Maybe we need to wear a helmet,

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.799
but we can all agree that the bicycle

00:09:00.799 --> 00:09:02.239
is not an invention that's going away

00:09:02.239 --> 00:09:04.400
and it's probably something that we should pay attention to.

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:08.719
For a different analogy,

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:10.960
does anybody in the audience play the cello?

00:09:12.559 --> 00:09:13.679
I don't know if we have a bias here,

00:09:13.679 --> 00:09:15.200
but that's way higher than I thought it would be.

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:20.000
Actually, well, I do not,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.400
but let's say you're going to go compose

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:24.239
a masterpiece concerto.

00:09:26.159 --> 00:09:28.640
You could ask some of these new AI capabilities

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:31.039
to go write that concerto for you

00:09:31.599 --> 00:09:32.799
and it would produce one

00:09:32.799 --> 00:09:34.479
that probably sounds pretty good,

00:09:34.479 --> 00:09:35.599
maybe is passable,

00:09:35.599 --> 00:09:39.440
maybe even for a naive listener like myself,

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:40.559
I would actually enjoy,

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:44.479
but it's not the concerto that you would write.

00:09:45.359 --> 00:09:46.400
Much in the same way,

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:48.559
these coding capabilities

00:09:48.559 --> 00:09:52.479
aren't going to produce what we are going to create.

00:09:53.119 --> 00:09:54.960
If I'm going to go make a new shiny app,

00:09:56.159 --> 00:09:57.919
part of the creation process

00:09:57.919 --> 00:10:00.159
is using the app itself,

00:10:00.159 --> 00:10:01.840
the creation of the app itself

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:05.119
to discover what it is I actually want to create.

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:06.719
So in that sense,

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:11.679
writing concertos and coding are contingent disciplines.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:14.080
Let's go back to Academy.

00:10:14.799 --> 00:10:18.559
I have here a very overly simplified curriculum

00:10:18.559 --> 00:10:20.320
of the foundations course,

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:24.000
and I would challenge you to find anything from this

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:25.039
that you would take out.

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:28.479
The curriculum itself is 10 weeks long

00:10:28.479 --> 00:10:31.520
and it actually really challenges the learners

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:33.440
to push them up to their limits

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:34.640
and learning capabilities.

00:10:35.679 --> 00:10:37.039
I'm not willing to take things out

00:10:37.039 --> 00:10:38.400
like summarizing data

00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:40.000
or certainly writing functions.

00:10:40.239 --> 00:10:40.960
So what do we do?

00:10:42.320 --> 00:10:43.200
We have 10 weeks

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:44.640
and we've really settled upon that

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:46.479
as an appropriate length of time for this.

00:10:47.039 --> 00:10:49.200
How do we introduce these AI coding assistants?

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:52.080
My suggestion here is to introduce them

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:54.080
gradually and intentionally.

00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:57.359
For example, let's say week three,

00:10:58.159 --> 00:11:00.239
you've just got exposed to the pipe,

00:11:00.239 --> 00:11:02.080
you can start to summarize your own data.

00:11:02.799 --> 00:11:04.000
Maybe it's now it's time for you

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:05.599
to use these AI coding assistants

00:11:05.599 --> 00:11:08.799
to do things like explain this piece of code,

00:11:08.880 --> 00:11:10.960
explain this piece of code that I don't understand,

00:11:11.679 --> 00:11:14.159
or maybe explain this piece of code from a peer

00:11:14.159 --> 00:11:15.359
who did something really cool.

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:19.039
You could also start to ask it to expand

00:11:19.039 --> 00:11:20.719
beyond your current abilities,

00:11:20.719 --> 00:11:22.239
maybe by just a little bit,

00:11:22.239 --> 00:11:24.719
doing things like show me how to group

00:11:24.719 --> 00:11:25.919
two columns together.

00:11:27.359 --> 00:11:29.039
Let's fast forward a few weeks later

00:11:29.039 --> 00:11:30.400
where you're starting to feel

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:31.840
a little bit more at ease

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:33.520
within a Markdown notebook,

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:37.359
maybe plotting is becoming something comfortable,

00:11:37.359 --> 00:11:38.719
something you're excited to show off

00:11:38.719 --> 00:11:39.840
to your colleagues,

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:42.159
and you've started to get annoyed

00:11:42.159 --> 00:11:43.440
with some spaghetti code.

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:44.479
Now it's time for you to write

00:11:44.479 --> 00:11:45.599
some of this into functions.

00:11:46.640 --> 00:11:48.400
That can be both tricky

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:50.400
and you probably also want to go

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:52.400
and document some of this as well.

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:54.640
Well, as many of you probably know,

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:57.200
these coding assistants are fantastic

00:11:57.200 --> 00:11:59.919
when it comes to writing documentation.

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:02.559
It also can maybe help you improve

00:12:02.559 --> 00:12:04.159
some inefficiencies in your code.

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:06.880
I've also found it's quite helpful

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:08.239
if you ask it to impersonate

00:12:08.799 --> 00:12:10.640
some of your favorite programmers out there.

00:12:11.359 --> 00:12:14.559
In fact, if I ask the coding assistant

00:12:14.559 --> 00:12:16.320
to write in the style of Hadley,

00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:17.840
it usually does a pretty good job.

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:20.080
As an aside, if you ask it to write

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:21.679
in the style of Max Kuhn,

00:12:21.679 --> 00:12:24.239
it ends up going back to about a decade ago

00:12:24.239 --> 00:12:27.119
and majorly favoring Carrot,

00:12:27.119 --> 00:12:28.880
but that will come with time.

00:12:30.719 --> 00:12:32.479
So let's fast forward to the end.

00:12:33.359 --> 00:12:35.200
You're almost done with your curriculum.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:36.080
It's time for you to go

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:39.440
and showcase some of the great creations

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:40.400
that have come about.

00:12:41.919 --> 00:12:44.640
Now's the time to really,

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:48.719
you know, get on that bike, so to speak.

00:12:48.719 --> 00:12:50.719
It's time for you to maybe go a bit faster.

00:12:52.479 --> 00:12:53.679
Now it's time to maybe bring

00:12:53.679 --> 00:12:54.799
some of these code assistants

00:12:54.799 --> 00:12:56.159
inside of your IDE.

00:12:56.159 --> 00:12:57.200
Maybe it's time for you to go pay

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:58.640
for a GitHub Copilot license,

00:12:59.599 --> 00:13:01.440
or you can go beyond the curriculum

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:03.039
that you've already been exposed to.

00:13:03.039 --> 00:13:04.559
Because these models have been trained

00:13:04.559 --> 00:13:06.799
on tremendous amounts of code.

00:13:06.799 --> 00:13:08.159
Looking at general ways

00:13:08.159 --> 00:13:10.000
people solve problems is a good question

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.280
you can ask of them.

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:12.479
Asking questions like,

00:13:12.479 --> 00:13:14.640
what packages should I explore next?

00:13:17.039 --> 00:13:20.640
So how can we change this experience

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:21.760
for these learners?

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:23.359
I think that's part of the answer,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.640
but I want to go back to close here

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:28.159
to threshold concepts again.

00:13:29.119 --> 00:13:31.440
Now I'll admit that threshold concepts

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:33.679
are supposed to be established ideas

00:13:33.679 --> 00:13:34.400
within a field.

00:13:35.599 --> 00:13:37.039
That's certainly not true

00:13:37.039 --> 00:13:39.520
with generative AI capabilities overall.

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:41.840
We're far from having clear established ideas

00:13:41.840 --> 00:13:42.400
in this space,

00:13:43.119 --> 00:13:44.960
but that doesn't mean we can't try.

00:13:46.159 --> 00:13:47.679
I'd love to hear from all of you

00:13:47.679 --> 00:13:49.599
of what you think the threshold concepts

00:13:49.599 --> 00:13:51.200
happen to be for these coding assistants.

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:53.760
Some that come to mind for me

00:13:53.760 --> 00:13:55.200
are drive faster,

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:56.880
but don't forget to steer.

00:13:56.880 --> 00:13:58.799
Coming back to that bicycle analogy again.

00:13:59.359 --> 00:14:01.440
Or maybe something like prompting matters.

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:04.799
Learning to use these capabilities is a skill.

00:14:05.919 --> 00:14:07.119
But I'm sure there's much more.

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:09.280
What comes to mind for you?

00:14:09.280 --> 00:14:09.919
Are these right?

00:14:09.919 --> 00:14:10.799
Do these resonate?

00:14:11.599 --> 00:14:13.200
Establishing these threshold concepts

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:14.400
I think will be critical

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:16.640
in successful adoption of these tools,

00:14:16.640 --> 00:14:19.359
which will keep us relevant as coders,

00:14:19.359 --> 00:14:20.960
but also make sure we're preparing

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:22.479
these new learners for the future.

00:14:23.919 --> 00:14:25.840
I want to finish with a huge thank you

00:14:25.840 --> 00:14:26.559
to all of the people

00:14:26.559 --> 00:14:28.799
who made our Academy program possible.

00:14:28.799 --> 00:14:30.559
I have Tony Sokolov in the audience here

00:14:30.559 --> 00:14:32.559
who's done a tremendous amount of work

00:14:32.559 --> 00:14:34.320
to make sure we identify the right people

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:36.239
who can participate from this program.

00:14:36.239 --> 00:14:38.000
And this has been a tremendous collaboration

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.479
with Posit that gets me excited

00:14:40.479 --> 00:14:41.280
to come to work.

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:42.400
And of course, to come here

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:43.760
to the conference as well.

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:45.359
So I want to thank you all for your time

00:14:45.359 --> 00:14:46.799
and I'm happy to answer any questions

00:14:46.799 --> 00:14:47.359
if you have them.

00:14:56.400 --> 00:14:58.000
Thank you so much, James.

00:14:58.479 --> 00:15:00.400
I have a question, actually.

00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:05.840
We've been listening to several talks

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:09.200
that speak about how generative AI

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:11.039
can augment your learning experience

00:15:11.039 --> 00:15:12.880
or augment your coding experience,

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:14.080
just like you talked about.

00:15:15.440 --> 00:15:16.320
At what point,

00:15:17.599 --> 00:15:19.520
when you're a little bit more advanced

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:20.400
at these concepts,

00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:21.679
at what point do you think

00:15:21.679 --> 00:15:23.760
it's reasonable or okay

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:25.919
to use generative AI tools

00:15:25.919 --> 00:15:27.440
to learn new concepts?

00:15:28.719 --> 00:15:30.239
Yeah, I think you can start with that

00:15:30.239 --> 00:15:32.000
quite early on, actually,

00:15:32.719 --> 00:15:35.119
especially if you can learn from examples.

00:15:35.119 --> 00:15:36.239
So if you have,

00:15:36.239 --> 00:15:37.919
if it's something that nobody's been,

00:15:37.919 --> 00:15:39.039
nobody has done before,

00:15:39.039 --> 00:15:41.039
you haven't seen somebody do before,

00:15:41.039 --> 00:15:42.400
that can certainly be a challenge

00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:43.599
because you're going to be

00:15:43.599 --> 00:15:44.640
pushing the constraints

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:46.559
of what the model has seen before.

00:15:46.559 --> 00:15:47.440
But if it's something,

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:48.719
if it's a new concept for you,

00:15:48.719 --> 00:15:51.200
but not a new concept for the community,

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:52.559
it's likely that you'll be starting

00:15:52.559 --> 00:15:53.919
from a pretty good place.

00:15:53.919 --> 00:15:56.400
But of course, the intuition

00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:57.520
that I'd like to give out there,

00:15:57.520 --> 00:15:59.119
I thought about including in this talk,

00:15:59.119 --> 00:16:00.400
but it's clippy, right?

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:01.840
So you have this useful assistance

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:03.039
on your desktop.

00:16:03.679 --> 00:16:05.440
Keep in mind that it has lots of context

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:06.880
that it can provide for you.

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:08.320
Of course it can be wrong,

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:10.239
but lots of my colleagues

00:16:10.239 --> 00:16:11.919
other than Tony are wrong as well.

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:13.599
And I still work with them

00:16:13.599 --> 00:16:15.440
and I still can learn from them as well.

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:18.239
That's great, thank you.

00:16:20.320 --> 00:16:22.320
So we actually have some viewers

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:23.440
in the virtual audience

00:16:23.440 --> 00:16:26.239
that don't know what Posit Academy is.

00:16:26.239 --> 00:16:28.640
Could you give like a very short rundown?

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:29.520
Absolutely.

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:31.119
So Posit Academy is an offering

00:16:31.119 --> 00:16:32.479
unsurprisingly from Posit

00:16:32.479 --> 00:16:35.119
that's a 10 week,

00:16:35.119 --> 00:16:37.840
somewhat intensive apprenticeship program

00:16:37.840 --> 00:16:39.679
that takes you from learning

00:16:39.679 --> 00:16:40.559
little to no code

00:16:40.559 --> 00:16:41.919
in either R or Python

00:16:41.919 --> 00:16:45.119
and gives you a curated curriculum

00:16:45.119 --> 00:16:46.799
that allows you to adopt the skills

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:48.080
that are going to be most relevant

00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:49.760
to you in your role.

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:51.919
So it'll include things

00:16:51.919 --> 00:16:52.719
like we talked about,

00:16:52.719 --> 00:16:54.880
summarizing data, creating visualizations.

00:16:55.200 --> 00:16:56.400
There's a lot of customization

00:16:56.400 --> 00:16:57.919
that can be applied to that.

00:16:57.919 --> 00:16:59.440
Probably one of the more important parts

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:00.799
about the whole program,

00:17:00.799 --> 00:17:03.760
in addition, aside from the wonderful mentors

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:05.439
that you get to work with from Posit

00:17:05.439 --> 00:17:06.560
is that it's project based.

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:09.040
So you get to apply what you're learning

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:10.800
on as close to a real data set

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:11.839
that's relevant to your work.

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:16.160
Amazing, thank you.

00:17:16.160 --> 00:17:18.880
So we have another question

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:20.880
that was kind of similar

00:17:20.880 --> 00:17:21.839
to what I asked before.

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:23.839
You gave examples

00:17:23.839 --> 00:17:25.920
of what packages should I explore next

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:28.560
or suggest ways to improve my code?

00:17:29.199 --> 00:17:30.800
What do you see as the dangers

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:32.719
of learners relying on an AI assistant

00:17:32.719 --> 00:17:33.520
for next steps?

00:17:34.560 --> 00:17:35.599
Yeah, so there's certainly,

00:17:35.599 --> 00:17:36.800
I mean, you can end up going

00:17:37.439 --> 00:17:38.959
in directions that

00:17:38.959 --> 00:17:40.800
maybe the field has moved beyond.

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:41.760
So I gave the example

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:44.160
of Max Kuhn with Carrot, right?

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:45.119
He would certainly recommend

00:17:45.119 --> 00:17:46.719
that you use tidy models these days.

00:17:47.760 --> 00:17:48.719
So that's the sort of thing,

00:17:48.719 --> 00:17:50.079
maybe the documentation

00:17:50.079 --> 00:17:51.520
isn't fully up to date.

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:52.560
It's possible that the code

00:17:52.560 --> 00:17:53.520
is going to be wrong.

00:17:54.319 --> 00:17:56.319
But it seems similar

00:17:56.319 --> 00:17:57.199
to maybe looking at

00:17:57.199 --> 00:17:59.680
a Stack Overflow post

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:01.599
where nobody has had a chance

00:18:01.599 --> 00:18:02.800
to upvote or something like that.

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:04.479
So the risks are different.

00:18:04.479 --> 00:18:06.880
The risks are now isolated

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:08.239
to your own experience

00:18:08.239 --> 00:18:09.040
with these agents.

00:18:09.599 --> 00:18:11.040
But it's not that,

00:18:11.040 --> 00:18:12.719
the experience is,

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:15.359
the same rules apply, right?

00:18:15.359 --> 00:18:16.800
Where you want to be skeptical

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:18.400
of code that you're going to go execute.

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:20.239
But these agents are getting better

00:18:20.239 --> 00:18:21.119
and better.

00:18:21.119 --> 00:18:22.400
And there's an incentive

00:18:22.719 --> 00:18:24.479
especially for the commercial ones,

00:18:24.479 --> 00:18:27.439
for them to align with things

00:18:27.439 --> 00:18:28.640
that aren't going to get you in trouble.

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:30.000
Right, right.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.079
And even from my own experience,

00:18:32.079 --> 00:18:32.800
I remember when

00:18:33.359 --> 00:18:35.040
some of the AI coding assistants

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:36.079
weren't even able

00:18:36.079 --> 00:18:37.280
to access the internet

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:39.359
and things have just improved incredibly.

00:18:39.359 --> 00:18:41.040
So, yep, good news.

00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:42.000
Hopefully that continues

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:42.880
on that trajectory.

00:18:44.319 --> 00:18:45.280
I think we have time

00:18:45.280 --> 00:18:46.479
for one more question here.

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:47.540
So,

00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:56.479
sorry, just reading this here.

00:18:56.479 --> 00:18:59.280
So, would Posit Academy

00:18:59.280 --> 00:18:59.920
benefit someone

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:00.800
who already has

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:02.000
a lot of coding experience

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.599
but lacks confidence with coding?

00:19:05.280 --> 00:19:07.680
So that would just perfectly describe

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:09.040
some of our initial cohorts.

00:19:09.040 --> 00:19:10.079
It was people who were

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:11.920
very enthusiastic

00:19:11.920 --> 00:19:14.239
and didn't identify as coders

00:19:14.239 --> 00:19:15.599
or data scientists for sure.

00:19:16.319 --> 00:19:17.520
They ended up being

00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:19.439
star students in the curriculum.

00:19:19.439 --> 00:19:19.939
And also,

00:19:22.319 --> 00:19:23.439
there's pluses and minuses

00:19:23.439 --> 00:19:24.079
to having people

00:19:24.079 --> 00:19:26.000
who have this advanced practice.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:26.719
You can inspire

00:19:26.719 --> 00:19:27.599
some of your cohort

00:19:27.599 --> 00:19:28.319
who maybe doesn't have

00:19:28.319 --> 00:19:30.319
the same level of experience as you do.

00:19:30.319 --> 00:19:32.319
But sometimes that can be intimidating.

00:19:32.319 --> 00:19:33.839
So you need to be mindful

00:19:33.839 --> 00:19:35.920
about the discrepancy

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:38.400
within an individual cohort

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:38.900
to match.

00:19:39.599 --> 00:19:41.040
It doesn't have to be perfectly matched.

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:43.599
But yeah, it certainly can give

00:19:43.599 --> 00:19:44.479
people a level of

00:19:45.359 --> 00:19:46.160
certification

00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:47.520
that maybe you don't get.

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:48.959
But if you're wondering yourself,

00:19:48.959 --> 00:19:50.800
if you need that certification,

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:52.880
Academy is great.

00:19:52.880 --> 00:19:53.920
But that's not,

00:19:53.920 --> 00:19:55.280
just getting a certificate

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:56.319
is not the reason to do it.

00:19:57.839 --> 00:19:59.040
I'm sure any of you

00:19:59.040 --> 00:19:59.680
who are feeling

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:00.959
self-conscious about that,

00:20:00.959 --> 00:20:01.680
you're doing great.

00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:02.560
We all feel that way.

00:20:05.439 --> 00:20:06.160
Thank you so much.

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:07.920
Thank you so much.

00:20:07.920 --> 00:20:09.439
And we really appreciate

00:20:09.439 --> 00:20:14.079
your talk today.

00:20:14.479 --> 00:20:15.380
Thank you.

